WEBVTT

00:06.582 --> 00:08.398
(woman yodeling)

00:08.417 --> 00:10.384
♪ ♪

00:15.683 --> 00:16.757
(yodeling stops)

00:16.925 --> 00:19.101
♪ ♪

00:23.599 --> 00:25.507
(crickets chirping)

00:25.601 --> 00:27.568
♪ ♪

00:41.600 --> 00:43.600
(puppies yipping)

00:43.693 --> 00:46.436
Congratulations, sir--
it's eight puppies.

00:46.455 --> 00:48.380
Four boys, three girls, and, uh,

00:48.532 --> 00:50.957
one who would prefer
not to be labeled yet.

00:51.052 --> 00:53.052
Excellent,
eight purebred puppies

00:53.203 --> 00:54.461
descended from the
first litter

00:54.613 --> 00:57.222
of Karl Friedrich Dobermann
himself.

00:57.391 --> 00:59.299
Smithers, you're in charge
of their training.

00:59.393 --> 01:01.635
Teach them all
the classic commands.

01:01.787 --> 01:03.303
Sit, stay...

01:03.397 --> 01:06.565
and bite striking workers
with your "wittle teefers."

01:06.734 --> 01:07.958
Yes, Mr. Burns.

01:07.976 --> 01:10.143
And you've allowed
the training dummies

01:10.237 --> 01:12.053
to fall into terrible disrepair.

01:12.147 --> 01:13.772
So I've ordered a new one.

01:13.999 --> 01:15.390
Here he is now.

01:15.409 --> 01:17.409
Um, I was told
there'd be a taco truck?

01:17.636 --> 01:20.137
Don't worry, their adult teeth
haven't come in yet.

01:20.155 --> 01:22.581
Just look out for
their much sharper baby teeth.

01:22.808 --> 01:24.708
-(puppies snarling)
-(Homer shouting)

01:25.811 --> 01:28.629
-(whimpers)
-Hmm. Hmm.

01:29.665 --> 01:31.315
(snarls)

01:31.333 --> 01:34.075
Ah, I guess
"Executive Kennel Supervisor"

01:34.169 --> 01:36.169
is all I'll ever be
to Mr. Burns.

01:36.263 --> 01:38.171
Nothing-- ow-- worse-- ow--

01:38.324 --> 01:40.324
than not being respected--
ow--

01:40.417 --> 01:41.749
at work! Ow!

01:41.918 --> 01:44.010
♪ ♪

01:44.163 --> 01:46.605
Ow, ow, ow, ow, ow.
Ow. (moans)

01:46.774 --> 01:49.608
Ow. Ow. Ow.

01:49.835 --> 01:52.277
-Ow.
-Aw!

01:53.172 --> 01:55.672
-(snarling)
-(grunting)

01:55.765 --> 01:57.691
(snarling)

01:57.843 --> 02:00.010
Ah, the puppies are finally

02:00.028 --> 02:01.436
murderous enough
to be doled out

02:01.455 --> 02:04.364
to my rich and powerful allies
who need watchdogs.

02:04.516 --> 02:06.533
Now to look through the pile
of bribes

02:06.685 --> 02:09.628
and see who's begging
hard enough to earn a puppy.

02:09.855 --> 02:13.857
Warren Buffett sent this box
of broken wooden pieces.

02:13.876 --> 02:15.175
Sir, that's a puzzle.

02:15.361 --> 02:16.526
(chuckles)
It certainly is a puzzle.

02:16.545 --> 02:19.304
What's his game,
sending me these misshapen bits?

02:19.456 --> 02:22.641
Uh, well, it's an activity
people do for fun.

02:22.792 --> 02:24.977
With their friends.
Perhaps you and I could--

02:25.128 --> 02:26.979
Perhaps you could
stop assuming familiarity

02:27.130 --> 02:28.221
with your betters.

02:28.374 --> 02:29.982
Now de-gunk the puppies' eyes!

02:30.133 --> 02:31.733
(Smithers groans sadly)

02:34.822 --> 02:36.989
(whimpering nearby)

02:38.659 --> 02:42.235
Oh, if only I'd been born
in a litter of puppies,

02:42.388 --> 02:44.479
then maybe someone
would love me.

02:44.573 --> 02:46.540
(clears his throat)
Simpson!

02:47.059 --> 02:48.725
(sniffles)

02:48.818 --> 02:51.244
Come on, Mr. Smithers,
you don't have to be lonely.

02:51.397 --> 02:53.246
You've totally got it going on.

02:53.399 --> 02:55.841
You've got that bow tie
and those glasses

02:56.068 --> 02:58.902
and that hunky nasal voice.

02:58.921 --> 03:01.346
Oh, sadly, the Springfield
dating pool is

03:01.498 --> 03:03.089
pretty bleak.

03:03.166 --> 03:05.333
It's always guys
who don't want to commit,

03:05.352 --> 03:07.928
or straight guys
who are going through a phase.

03:08.080 --> 03:09.837
<i> Disco Stu is</i>

03:09.857 --> 03:12.173
<i> hetero-flexible. Ooh!</i>

03:12.267 --> 03:15.009
(sighs) I just want someone
to be there when I get home.

03:15.103 --> 03:17.845
Someone who loves me
unconditionally.

03:17.865 --> 03:19.847
Oh, yeah, that's the good stuff.

03:19.867 --> 03:21.942
It's the conditions
that'll kill ya.

03:22.094 --> 03:24.519
Mr. Smithers, I'm gonna
find you a man-Marge.

03:24.613 --> 03:26.780
Look at this guy--
he seems perfect!

03:26.932 --> 03:28.523
That's me.

03:28.617 --> 03:30.100
Oh, yeah.

03:30.193 --> 03:32.336
Well, it is
a much younger picture.

03:33.530 --> 03:35.530
Goodbye. Thank you for the oil.

03:35.549 --> 03:36.773
I love it.

03:36.942 --> 03:38.032
Excellent.

03:38.126 --> 03:40.034
Well, that's the last
of the litter.

03:40.054 --> 03:42.946
Oh, except for you.

03:43.039 --> 03:45.115
You're no killer,
with those soft eyes

03:45.133 --> 03:46.708
and kind disposition.

03:46.802 --> 03:49.427
You've brought shame to
the very notion of inbreeding.

03:49.580 --> 03:50.878
Go on, bite him.

03:50.973 --> 03:53.148
Bite his doughy face.

03:53.901 --> 03:55.901
(groans)

03:56.128 --> 03:58.295
Who's gonna take you home?

03:58.464 --> 04:00.130
I hope they find you a dictator

04:00.299 --> 04:01.740
who's as sweet as you are.

04:01.891 --> 04:03.075
Or...

04:03.302 --> 04:04.910
how about a Fortune 500
fashion designer

04:05.079 --> 04:08.396
who's already made a matching
suit for the puppy?

04:08.474 --> 04:11.250
Good muscle tone, needy,
with a slight drooling problem.

04:11.401 --> 04:13.961
Reminds me of my last boyfriend.

04:14.070 --> 04:18.090
HOMER:
<i> His last girlfriend was a boy?</i>

04:18.241 --> 04:21.551
Your last girlfriend was a boy?

04:22.671 --> 04:25.747
(speaking in Mandarin)

04:25.766 --> 04:26.765
(knocking)

04:26.916 --> 04:28.341
Oh, I'm sorry. I was just...

04:28.435 --> 04:30.510
Negotiating the sale
of excess Kilowatt hours

04:30.604 --> 04:31.937
to a Chinese server farm.

04:32.164 --> 04:33.847
And you got a very good deal.

04:33.999 --> 04:34.848
Mm.

04:34.942 --> 04:35.665
I also speak Mandarin.

04:35.684 --> 04:37.109
I'm Michael de Graaf,

04:37.336 --> 04:40.170
and I flew here from my villa
in Milan to claim this puppy.

04:40.263 --> 04:43.340
I can offer Burns a priceless
Impressionist painting.

04:43.358 --> 04:46.343
Mr. Burns' collection
could use a Manet...

04:46.436 --> 04:49.955
Well, I've got a Monet and a guy
who can change O's to A's.

04:50.106 --> 04:52.365
Mm, Mr. Burns would never know
the difference.

04:52.518 --> 04:55.443
He hates art-- he just wants
to keep it out of museums.

04:55.462 --> 04:57.354
But first I told him
you have some questions

04:57.372 --> 05:00.615
about what the puppy's
looking for in a companion.

05:00.634 --> 05:03.543
Well, uh, this is
an unusual Dobermann.

05:03.637 --> 05:06.471
Uh, are you prepared
for a dog that's sweet,

05:06.623 --> 05:08.974
maybe a little shy,
but just wants to give his heart

05:09.201 --> 05:10.867
to someone who loves him?

05:10.886 --> 05:13.036
He sounds
like a dream come true.

05:13.055 --> 05:15.147
Okay, the puppy's yours,
Mr. de Graaf.

05:15.298 --> 05:16.982
Please, it's Michael.

05:17.133 --> 05:18.817
This calls for a celebration.

05:19.044 --> 05:20.635
Are you free for dinner tonight?

05:20.729 --> 05:21.728
I'm sorry?

05:21.880 --> 05:23.396
You're talented,
smart as a whip,

05:23.549 --> 05:26.658
and hot in a 1960s
Cape Canaveral kind of way.

05:26.885 --> 05:28.885
I'd love to take you on a date.

05:28.978 --> 05:30.887
Well, I'd love...

05:30.980 --> 05:33.457
to say yes!

05:35.060 --> 05:36.242
♪ ♪

05:36.395 --> 05:39.079
I love this place!
It's so old school.

05:39.231 --> 05:41.840
It reminds me of my childhood--
laminated menus,

05:42.067 --> 05:45.235
fossilized Parmesan,
problematic murals.

05:45.253 --> 05:47.679
-(Michael chuckles)
-Welcome-a to Luigi's.

05:47.906 --> 05:49.848
Italiana food for everybody.

05:49.999 --> 05:53.185
I put a-salt and a-pepper
on the table,

05:53.412 --> 05:55.428
but for you,
such a handsome couple,

05:55.522 --> 05:58.339
if you want-a pepper
and-a pepper,

05:58.433 --> 06:00.917
hey, that's a-wonderful, too!

06:00.936 --> 06:04.011
(both laugh)

06:04.180 --> 06:05.864
Vintage vinyl.

06:06.015 --> 06:07.866
Add some spikes to it,
and you've got half

06:08.017 --> 06:09.759
of Vivienne Westwood's career.

06:09.853 --> 06:10.777
(laughs)

06:10.929 --> 06:12.262
Okay, that was a fake laugh.

06:12.373 --> 06:15.115
I was afraid to admit I don't
know anything about fashion.

06:15.209 --> 06:17.709
Oh, that's so refreshing.

06:17.936 --> 06:20.437
People usually want
to date me to get into<i> GQ,</i>

06:20.530 --> 06:23.382
meet Anna Wintour, or co-parent
Anderson Cooper's baby.

06:23.609 --> 06:26.051
I guess that was
just Anderson Cooper.

06:26.202 --> 06:30.138
Waylon, you are like
no one I've ever met.

06:31.133 --> 06:33.266
(muttering in Italian)

06:34.953 --> 06:37.062
Mamma, no!
God-a loves everybody!

06:37.289 --> 06:39.356
(shouting in Italian)

06:40.626 --> 06:43.460
But what about Uncle Benito
and the roommate

06:43.553 --> 06:45.812
he always-a brings
to Easter supper?

06:45.964 --> 06:47.406
(spits)

06:47.557 --> 06:50.634
Mamma, no! Do not put
a hex on their ziti!

06:50.727 --> 06:52.994
(both laughing)

06:53.805 --> 06:55.747
♪ ♪

06:57.400 --> 07:00.310
People like me should spend
more time in flyover country,

07:00.403 --> 07:02.495
see what America's really like.

07:02.589 --> 07:05.090
More like fly-around country.
Planes won't go near us

07:05.317 --> 07:08.093
because of all the teens
with laser pointers.

07:10.989 --> 07:13.247
(sighs) It's a shame
you have to leave tomorrow.

07:13.341 --> 07:14.841
Oh, I'm canceling my flight.

07:14.935 --> 07:16.159
Why?

07:16.178 --> 07:17.327
Because it would be much harder

07:17.420 --> 07:20.439
to fall in love with you
from Milan.

07:22.776 --> 07:24.668
(shivering)

07:24.761 --> 07:26.336
Homer, what happened?

07:26.354 --> 07:28.188
I can feel it--
my fix-up is working.

07:28.340 --> 07:30.857
I changed the destiny
of two human beings.

07:31.009 --> 07:33.526
I am a gay matchmaking God!

07:33.620 --> 07:36.346
What about some straight
matchmaking for us?

07:36.364 --> 07:39.332
(scoffs)
I'm a God, not a miracle worker.

07:45.299 --> 07:47.040
And he posted you
on his Instagram?

07:47.192 --> 07:49.876
Cute caption? Gay couple emoji?
(gasps)

07:49.970 --> 07:52.119
(singsongy):
I'm excited!

07:52.139 --> 07:53.472
What was that?

07:53.640 --> 07:55.031
Oh, just guy stuff.

07:55.124 --> 07:57.124
Smithers was updating me
on his boyfriend.

07:57.144 --> 07:59.126
-Boyfriend?
-Yeah, no big deal.

07:59.295 --> 08:01.963
I kind of fixed Smithers up
with a dude I know.

08:02.057 --> 08:03.482
Now they're going steady.
No big deal.

08:03.709 --> 08:05.800
Wait, wait,
I just have one question.

08:05.894 --> 08:07.727
Can I ask you
a thousand questions?

08:07.821 --> 08:10.197
Sorry, Marge, late for work.

08:10.991 --> 08:12.991
(birds chirping)

08:13.218 --> 08:15.218
-Tell me everything!
-(shrieks)

08:15.311 --> 08:17.662
Um, they've been dating
for six weeks or so.

08:17.814 --> 08:18.830
You probably
don't even know him.

08:19.057 --> 08:20.223
He's some fashion designer guy.

08:20.242 --> 08:21.574
Michael de Graaf.

08:21.727 --> 08:22.834
<i> What?</i>

08:23.003 --> 08:25.319
Smithers is dating
Michael de Graaf,

08:25.339 --> 08:29.156
the judge on seasons ten through
15 of<i> America's Got Fabric?</i>

08:29.251 --> 08:32.068
He has my favorite catchphrase!

08:32.161 --> 08:34.495
<i> Now, that is avant-gorgeous.</i>

08:34.589 --> 08:36.681
<i> Oh, my God, honey,</i>
<i> you got catchphrased.</i>

08:36.833 --> 08:40.093
And he's even more famous
for his savage zings.

08:40.262 --> 08:42.412
<i>I don't know.</i>
<i>It's a little</i> Sex and the City.

08:42.430 --> 08:45.857
<i> If there were no sex</i>
<i> and the city was Milwaukee.</i>

08:46.009 --> 08:47.192
(chuckles)

08:47.343 --> 08:50.195
They dress so bad in Milwaukee.

08:50.422 --> 08:51.345
I assume.

08:51.365 --> 08:52.364
Hmm?

08:53.367 --> 08:54.449
(groans)

08:55.369 --> 08:57.594
I have to meet Michael de Graaf!

08:57.763 --> 09:00.354
Okay, okay. When they come back
from their trip.

09:00.374 --> 09:03.099
Ooh, whisked off
by a billionaire.

09:03.192 --> 09:05.544
How romantic. Where did they go?

09:05.695 --> 09:08.195
Well, Smithers says they're
too young for Provincetown,

09:08.215 --> 09:10.123
too monogamous for Fire Island

09:10.217 --> 09:12.942
and you know
how Waylon gets in Palm Springs.

09:12.961 --> 09:14.052
No, I don't!

09:14.203 --> 09:16.596
I don't know anything!

09:21.469 --> 09:22.727
Yeah, it's pretty sweet

09:22.879 --> 09:25.713
to completely alter
the course of people's lives.

09:25.791 --> 09:27.715
If it goes great, I'm a genius.

09:27.734 --> 09:28.808
<i> If it goes south,</i>

09:28.902 --> 09:31.144
<i> I just turn off my phone.</i>

09:31.238 --> 09:34.480
Ah, a beautiful resort,

09:34.633 --> 09:35.907
a turquoise ocean.

09:36.134 --> 09:37.801
The only thing missing
is Christine Baranski

09:37.894 --> 09:39.302
singing "Dancing Queen."

09:39.395 --> 09:41.654
I thought you might say that.

09:41.748 --> 09:43.898
("Dancing Queen" playing)

09:44.025 --> 09:47.160
♪<i> Friday night</i>
<i> and the lights are low</i> ♪

09:47.312 --> 09:51.072
♪<i> Looking out</i>
<i> for a place to go</i> ♪

09:51.091 --> 09:53.240
Oh, my God!
How much did that cost?

09:53.409 --> 09:54.593
Less than you might think.

09:54.669 --> 09:56.836
-Oh, and I got you
something else.
-Oh.

09:56.913 --> 09:58.338
I call it the Waylon.

09:58.490 --> 10:00.915
Like you,
it's sophisticated yet playful,

10:00.934 --> 10:02.992
as blue and sparkling
as your eyes.

10:03.011 --> 10:04.510
Okay, I've got to go.

10:04.587 --> 10:07.997
I'm helping a 13-year-old boy
come out to his parents.

10:08.166 --> 10:10.350
To Jacksonville!

10:10.502 --> 10:15.672
♪<i> Digging</i>
<i> the dancing queen...!</i> ♪

10:15.765 --> 10:17.523
(song ends)

10:17.676 --> 10:19.008
(bird caws)

10:19.027 --> 10:21.361
(panting)
Sorry I'm late, sir.

10:21.455 --> 10:23.680
A-And sorry I wasn't available
this weekend.

10:23.773 --> 10:25.439
Or last weekend. I was...

10:25.459 --> 10:26.774
You were gone?
(chuckles)

10:26.793 --> 10:28.534
Who cares? I figured it out.

10:28.687 --> 10:30.462
These pieces are designed
to interlock.

10:30.689 --> 10:32.446
But to what purpose?

10:32.615 --> 10:33.857
Sir, it is a puzzle.

10:33.875 --> 10:35.191
Not for long, man.

10:35.284 --> 10:37.135
Monty Burns is on the case.

10:37.395 --> 10:41.723
The obvious first step is
to sort every piece by weight.

10:45.871 --> 10:46.978
-Waylon!
-(gasps)

10:47.205 --> 10:49.873
Marge? Why are you
in the executive parking lot?

10:49.891 --> 10:50.965
Who cares?

10:51.059 --> 10:53.376
Tell me
all about Michael de Graaf!

10:53.395 --> 10:56.546
(chuckles)
Well, Michael's kind of perfect.

10:56.564 --> 10:58.381
Attentive,
treats me like an equal,

10:58.400 --> 11:00.066
has never trap-doored
an entire Girl Scout troop

11:00.218 --> 11:01.551
because they were out
of Thin Mints.

11:01.720 --> 11:04.404
I mean, it's nice to finally be
in love with someone...

11:04.556 --> 11:05.163
good.

11:05.314 --> 11:06.998
I'm dying to meet him.

11:07.150 --> 11:10.059
What if we threw you two
a party?

11:10.078 --> 11:11.744
A party. That's what people do

11:11.897 --> 11:13.838
when they finally have
something worth celebrating.

11:13.990 --> 11:16.065
-Let's do it!
-Yes!

11:16.159 --> 11:18.902
This makes me part
of your couple origin story.

11:18.920 --> 11:19.903
I'm in!

11:19.921 --> 11:21.638
(low, upbeat music plays)

11:23.833 --> 11:25.742
Just what I always wanted
for him,

11:25.835 --> 11:27.835
a handsome
billionaire boyfriend.

11:27.929 --> 11:29.187
So happy.

11:29.414 --> 11:30.246
(grunts)

11:30.265 --> 11:31.839
Excuse me, Mr. de Graaf,

11:32.008 --> 11:34.417
we love your wicked zingers
on the show.

11:34.436 --> 11:35.360
Could you?

11:35.511 --> 11:36.361
My pleasure.

11:36.588 --> 11:38.438
Wow, it was so kind
of Estelle Getty

11:38.590 --> 11:41.348
to donate her wardrobe for
your production of<i> The Crucible.</i>

11:41.368 --> 11:42.275
(laughs)

11:42.427 --> 11:44.928
Hello and welcome
to Grey Gardens.

11:45.021 --> 11:46.854
At least
those ladies had a look.

11:46.873 --> 11:48.707
You have a "don't look."

11:48.934 --> 11:50.600
(laughing)

11:50.693 --> 11:51.543
Do you like my top?

11:51.770 --> 11:53.194
Yes, I love the shoulder pads.

11:53.362 --> 11:56.122
Is something I would have said
in the '90s but not about that.

11:56.216 --> 11:57.716
Do you like my top?

11:57.867 --> 11:59.968
Yes. He seems very nice.

12:01.037 --> 12:03.221
Is it wrong
to enjoy being envied?

12:03.372 --> 12:05.465
Because I am savoring it.

12:05.617 --> 12:07.967
When did you first realize
that Homer was the one,

12:08.136 --> 12:09.969
the great love of your life?

12:10.063 --> 12:12.546
Well, after he got me pregnant,

12:12.566 --> 12:15.567
I just knew he was someone
I was gonna have kids with.

12:15.794 --> 12:17.293
Aw. Mwah.

12:17.386 --> 12:19.887
Young lady, I like
your quirky fashion sense.

12:19.906 --> 12:22.148
That zigzag dress hem
is everything.

12:22.300 --> 12:25.134
Thanks, but I don't
really pay attention to fashion.

12:25.228 --> 12:28.137
It doesn't seem...
super important.

12:28.139 --> 12:30.564
I'd like to suggest
some alterations. May I?

12:30.584 --> 12:33.659
I mean, it's a waste
of your time, but fine.

12:33.812 --> 12:35.736
Wearing the same thing
every day is a choice,

12:35.756 --> 12:38.831
so I can free up my mind
to think about important things,

12:38.984 --> 12:40.908
rather than "Am I on trend?"

12:40.927 --> 12:42.927
Ha, whatever that means.

12:43.096 --> 12:44.837
You know who didn't care
about fashion?

12:44.931 --> 12:46.264
Ruth Bader Ginsburg.

12:46.491 --> 12:48.508
She slapped on a doily
and that was enough.

12:48.660 --> 12:51.677
This obsession with appearance
in our culture...

12:51.772 --> 12:52.845
Did you make me taller?

12:52.939 --> 12:54.347
I feel so confident.

12:54.516 --> 12:58.334
I don't even have a job, but
I'm going to ask for a raise.

12:58.353 --> 12:59.319
(grunts)

13:00.672 --> 13:02.447
A toast to our hosts.

13:02.598 --> 13:04.023
And to Marge's hair,

13:04.175 --> 13:06.433
which is avant-gorgeous.

13:06.528 --> 13:07.860
(chuckles):
Oh!

13:07.954 --> 13:09.621
And I want you to be
the first to hear--

13:09.772 --> 13:12.015
I've decided to manufacture
my new retail line

13:12.033 --> 13:13.533
right here in Springfield,

13:13.627 --> 13:16.853
in the factory that used
to make fidget spinners.

13:16.855 --> 13:18.371
Spin-ners!

13:18.465 --> 13:21.024
And if anyone needs a job,
there are applications

13:21.042 --> 13:24.710
right next to the best coleslaw
I've ever had.

13:24.863 --> 13:26.304
MARGE:
Ooh-hoo!

13:26.455 --> 13:27.806
(cheering)

13:27.957 --> 13:28.807
(grumbles)

13:29.034 --> 13:31.050
Mamma, everyone is-a happy.

13:31.202 --> 13:34.312
Why are you so against
this-a love? Why?

13:34.463 --> 13:35.872
I hate...

13:35.965 --> 13:38.465
because I hate-a myself!

13:38.560 --> 13:41.210
I... I love-a the women.

13:41.212 --> 13:43.488
No, Mamma, you are beautiful.

13:43.715 --> 13:46.324
You love-a the women,
and I love-a the you.

13:46.475 --> 13:48.384
(both crying)

13:48.477 --> 13:52.738
I had a pillow
of-a Gina Lollobrigida

13:52.833 --> 13:54.223
that I used to, oh...

13:54.317 --> 13:56.317
(speaking Italian)

13:56.411 --> 13:59.128
Oh, oh, okay, okay, okay, Mamma!

14:00.398 --> 14:02.841
(gasps) Look,
it's Michael's new factory!

14:03.068 --> 14:04.325
So modern.

14:04.419 --> 14:05.585
Can we look inside?

14:05.737 --> 14:07.737
Yeah, do you know anybody
that works there?

14:07.830 --> 14:10.423
Ha, well, they hired
most of the desperate saps

14:10.517 --> 14:11.832
who've been unemployed forever.

14:12.001 --> 14:13.334
So, yeah,
I'm friends with all of 'em.

14:13.353 --> 14:16.521
This week's trend
is glitter on sunglasses.

14:16.672 --> 14:18.398
So we got right on it.

14:25.773 --> 14:26.939
(coughs)

14:27.033 --> 14:29.275
What happens
to all the toxic stuff?

14:29.427 --> 14:31.661
It gets off-glittered
through the chimney.

14:32.764 --> 14:34.097
(geese honking)

14:34.115 --> 14:37.458
(distressed honking)

14:39.120 --> 14:41.270
Hey, look at me,
I'm a working stiff!

14:41.289 --> 14:43.940
Very stiff. These chemicals
are giving me a condition

14:44.033 --> 14:47.135
my doctor calls
"living rigor mortis."

14:47.888 --> 14:49.095
(yells)

14:50.632 --> 14:53.374
No wonder fast fashion
is so inexpensive.

14:53.468 --> 14:55.727
This place is terrible
for the environment.

14:55.878 --> 14:57.470
And it's a sweatshop!

14:57.622 --> 15:00.565
No, sweetie,
it's a sweatpants shop.

15:00.716 --> 15:03.902
Which are made with Lycra,
which leaches into the sea.

15:04.053 --> 15:06.905
Our oceans
are now ten percent spandex.

15:07.056 --> 15:09.073
Well, then they'll fit the Earth
more snugly.

15:09.300 --> 15:10.742
Dad, how can Michael allow this?

15:10.818 --> 15:13.653
I thought gay people were
supposed to be better than us.

15:13.805 --> 15:14.895
You mean our boss?

15:14.973 --> 15:15.914
He knows.

15:16.065 --> 15:18.166
♪ ♪

15:19.586 --> 15:22.587
No. Michael's the perfect guy
for Smithers.

15:22.814 --> 15:24.571
I picked him out!

15:24.591 --> 15:26.240
I fixed them up!

15:26.259 --> 15:30.094
My gay matchmaking reputation
is ruined!

15:30.321 --> 15:32.722
The human suffering is bad, too.

15:38.104 --> 15:40.680
(sighs) How do I tell Smithers
that the love of his life

15:40.848 --> 15:42.256
is running a sweatshop?

15:42.275 --> 15:43.757
Hey, look,
you tried to play God,

15:43.777 --> 15:45.334
and now, like God,

15:45.503 --> 15:49.338
you get to stand back and laugh
at all the losers' suffering.

15:49.432 --> 15:51.007
Ha-ha.

15:51.009 --> 15:52.617
Ah, losers.

15:52.844 --> 15:56.454
Oh, who knew gay relationships
could be complicated?

15:56.681 --> 15:59.273
(men moaning)

15:59.367 --> 16:01.608
Man, tough day on the line.

16:01.628 --> 16:05.946
Another guy lost an arm
to the spaghetti strap slicer.

16:05.966 --> 16:08.207
Oh, I don't feel so good.

16:08.301 --> 16:11.694
I think I spent too much time
in the tie-dye chamber.

16:11.713 --> 16:13.012
(coughs)

16:13.807 --> 16:14.955
You think that's bad?

16:14.975 --> 16:17.725
I got to go break a guy's heart.

16:19.628 --> 16:21.128
There he is!

16:21.222 --> 16:22.629
The man who showed me
that love is real

16:22.649 --> 16:25.541
and there is a man
at the end of the rainbow.

16:25.560 --> 16:29.153
Oof. Speaking of showing you
things you didn't know,

16:29.380 --> 16:31.698
look what his factory's done
to Lake Springfield.

16:33.401 --> 16:34.717
Wha...? (gasps)

16:34.736 --> 16:37.053
HOMER:
It's gone plaid.

16:37.146 --> 16:39.146
(groans) M-Michael
must have an explanation.

16:39.165 --> 16:40.147
He-He's a good man.

16:40.316 --> 16:41.891
Uh, I just need advice

16:41.909 --> 16:43.668
from someone who understands
the ethical challenges

16:43.895 --> 16:45.728
faced by business leaders.

16:45.747 --> 16:49.065
Smithers,
I've made amazing progress.

16:49.158 --> 16:51.067
By giving this enigma
my undivided attention,

16:51.160 --> 16:53.919
I've proven conclusively
these pieces form...

16:54.072 --> 16:55.829
a secret image.

16:55.998 --> 16:57.406
I can't believe
I'm asking<i> you</i> this,

16:57.500 --> 17:00.409
but I-I have a question about,
uh...

17:00.428 --> 17:01.519
my love life.

17:01.670 --> 17:03.688
Indeed.
Tell me about the lucky lady.

17:03.915 --> 17:05.097
-Man.
-Oh. What's her...

17:05.191 --> 17:06.265
-His.
-...name?

17:06.359 --> 17:08.842
-Michael.
-Michelle. Such a lovely name.

17:08.862 --> 17:10.010
And, uh, what does she...

17:10.104 --> 17:11.178
-He.
-...do?

17:11.197 --> 17:12.421
Well, that's just it, sir.

17:12.440 --> 17:14.348
He's the CEO of a major company.

17:14.442 --> 17:16.108
He's wonderful to me,
but I-I'm worried

17:16.202 --> 17:19.095
he might ruthlessly care
about nothing but profit.

17:19.113 --> 17:20.538
Ooh, don't tell me,

17:20.765 --> 17:22.022
is it Sheryl Sandberg?

17:22.042 --> 17:23.541
No, it's Michael de Graaf.

17:23.692 --> 17:25.935
Michael de Graaf?
Smithers, you fool.

17:26.028 --> 17:27.436
Marry that man right now.

17:27.455 --> 17:30.773
-What?
-So you have to pretend
to be gay-- who cares?

17:30.792 --> 17:32.124
He's a billionaire.

17:32.277 --> 17:34.135
Come, you must see.

17:34.962 --> 17:36.429
SMITHERS:
A denim fire?

17:37.465 --> 17:39.390
De Graaf's discovered
the secret.

17:39.542 --> 17:42.952
Fast fashion is far more toxic
than nuclear power.

17:43.045 --> 17:46.046
-It's worse?
-Nuclear energy gives people
warmth and light.

17:46.107 --> 17:48.958
This guy is profiting
off a product nobody needs:

17:49.051 --> 17:51.644
a constant stream
of brand-new skinnied jeans

17:51.796 --> 17:54.072
and be-cropped tops.

17:55.316 --> 17:57.700
Look what they've done
to Blinky.

18:00.080 --> 18:02.747
Our toxins may have created
the three-eyed fish,

18:02.898 --> 18:04.473
but we never managed to kill it.

18:04.567 --> 18:06.617
You've got yourself
one hell of a guy.

18:06.769 --> 18:09.295
Don't let him slip away.

18:12.408 --> 18:14.425
(explosion)

18:15.911 --> 18:18.170
(gasps) I always thought
a Chernobyl in Springfield

18:18.323 --> 18:20.172
would be caused
by my horrible boss,

18:20.325 --> 18:22.391
not my perfect boyfriend.

18:24.495 --> 18:27.730
♪ ♪

18:39.435 --> 18:41.344
Something's clogging the engine!

18:41.362 --> 18:43.696
My God, it's loungewear.

18:43.848 --> 18:46.165
Loungewear!

18:47.794 --> 18:51.462
Michael, your factory
is literally a toxic workplace.

18:51.614 --> 18:52.872
Don't worry, sweetie.

18:52.966 --> 18:55.282
I've got an amazing
crisis management company.

18:55.301 --> 18:57.193
They're the ones
who squelched the story

18:57.286 --> 19:00.221
that Peloton seats
are made from dolphin faces.

19:02.049 --> 19:04.533
-(explosion)
-(yells)
-If I'm making clothes

19:04.627 --> 19:06.460
for Tommy Target
and Wendy Walmart,

19:06.554 --> 19:07.645
they have to be cheap.

19:07.796 --> 19:08.888
Because in fast fashion,

19:08.982 --> 19:11.131
whoever cuts
the most corners wins.

19:11.225 --> 19:14.652
(cries) I can't believe
I fell in love with a monster.

19:14.803 --> 19:18.381
Really? It seems to me that you
have a pretty consistent type.

19:18.399 --> 19:19.306
Ah.

19:19.400 --> 19:21.808
-(explosion)
-Exquisite.

19:21.828 --> 19:22.976
Is that acid?

19:23.070 --> 19:24.829
No, molten sports bra.

19:24.980 --> 19:27.239
Waylon, you deserve
Milan, Paris,

19:27.333 --> 19:29.834
at the very least,
a town with a Chipotle.

19:30.061 --> 19:31.894
I love that you care
about what's right,

19:32.063 --> 19:34.172
but, for once,
do what's right for you.

19:34.323 --> 19:37.066
Come away with me and be adored.

19:37.084 --> 19:40.219
(sighs)
Adored would be a nice change.

19:44.258 --> 19:46.759
To seeing the best in each other

19:46.853 --> 19:48.835
and ignoring everything else.

19:48.855 --> 19:51.096
I'll drink to that.

19:51.249 --> 19:52.748
-(yaps)
-Ooh! Idiot!

19:52.767 --> 19:56.510
These pants are made of cashmere
and shredded Picassos.

19:56.604 --> 19:58.196
(whimpers)

19:59.090 --> 20:00.698
(whimpers)

20:02.702 --> 20:05.578
♪ ♪

20:07.448 --> 20:08.447
Buck up, pal.

20:08.599 --> 20:10.616
Beautiful jet-setting
gay billionaires

20:10.768 --> 20:12.543
are a dime a dozen in this town.

20:12.695 --> 20:15.028
(sighs) It's gonna take
some time to get over Michael.

20:15.122 --> 20:17.739
But I did get one thing out
of the relationship.

20:18.776 --> 20:20.793
Someone to be there
when I come home,

20:20.945 --> 20:23.462
who will love me
unconditionally.

20:23.556 --> 20:24.705
(chuckles softly)

20:25.633 --> 20:29.060
You're the one hound
I'll never release.

